    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_374506827" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/374506827" />
    <a title="Jonathan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3802964-jonathan"><img alt="Jonathan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1275239052p2/3802964.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/374506827?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan" href="/user/show/3802964-jonathan">Jonathan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer374506827" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15593946532169125975">I&apos;d hazard a guess that this is one of Shane McGowan&apos;s favourite books. Personally, I found the wife-punching, baby-smothering, lying, stealing gobshite of the title utterly charmless. Reading the reviews, however, he&apos;s apparently a delightful comic rapscallion. Perhaps this sort of thing was daring and bawdy back in the uptight 1950s. <br/><br/>If, like me, Dangerfield&apos;s sozzled transatlantic blarney leaves you cold, you are left with the world&apos;s most unconvincing sex-machine (with the possible exception</span>
  <span id="freeText15593946532169125975" style="display:none">I'd hazard a guess that this is one of Shane McGowan's favourite books. Personally, I found the wife-punching, baby-smothering, lying, stealing gobshite of the title utterly charmless. Reading the reviews, however, he's apparently a delightful comic rapscallion. Perhaps this sort of thing was daring and bawdy back in the uptight 1950s. <br /><br />If, like me, Dangerfield's sozzled transatlantic blarney leaves you cold, you are left with the world's most unconvincing sex-machine (with the possible exception of Reg Varney in On The Buses). Sure, Dangerfield wins all his fights, outwits all his pursuers and beds all the women, but only because of Donleavy's benevolence. Suspension of disbelief is one thing, but we're away with the fairies as far as plausibility goes here. And the book simply reeks of misogyny. There are only so many times women (who, it seems, are only good for one thing) can be hit, verbally abused or get covered in excrement before your eyes start to roll uncontrollably in your head. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15593946532169125975" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

