  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_138786751" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/138786751" />
    <a title="Laura Leaney" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3633494-laura-leaney"><img alt="Laura Leaney" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592839426p2/3633494.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/138786751?book_show_action=true">Jan 05, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura Leaney" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura Leaney" href="/user/show/3633494-laura-leaney">Laura Leaney</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer138786751" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11534951469863429194">Oh my Irish stars, I&apos;m glad as hell to be done with this novel. I did laugh. But I also cried at how long I had to spend in the head and world of Sebastian Dangerfield, an American with the English, no Irish, accent of the permanently inebriated. I&apos;m no delicate flower, but Dangerfield&apos;s gross debauchery left me &quot;cold as a eunuch&apos;s balls on the quays.&quot; At one point he calls one of his adulterous escapades &quot;bestial bedlam.&quot; And it is. Wife and baby at home, too busy freezing to worry about starvi</span>
  <span id="freeText11534951469863429194" style="display:none">Oh my Irish stars, I'm glad as hell to be done with this novel. I did laugh. But I also cried at how long I had to spend in the head and world of Sebastian Dangerfield, an American with the English, no Irish, accent of the permanently inebriated. I'm no delicate flower, but Dangerfield's gross debauchery left me "cold as a eunuch's balls on the quays." At one point he calls one of his adulterous escapades "bestial bedlam." And it is. Wife and baby at home, too busy freezing to worry about starving. And Dangerfield? Out feckin' around - admiring the female arse, getting thrown out of bars, or leaving his little dangler out on the train for all to see. Cute.<br /><br />I loved the power of the stream of consciousness narrative though. At first, I found it irritating. Was I reading third person? First? I got into the swing though. Some absolutely brilliant lines. A sample:<br /><br />"Eight o'clock. The streets were wet, puddles of water on the granite blocks. Western clouds swarming soundlessly catching up the turf smell from the steaming chimney pots on this chill Saturday night. Bird feet moving his soul through this Danish city. The hoarse voices of newsboys punctuating the corners of streets behind. Up here in White Friar Street I can hear them saying rosaries. And in the hospital window, the light goes on and a nurse pulls down the shade."<br /><br />That's really lovely. Ghastly character (which is not a crime, I admit) but tremendously interesting writing. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11534951469863429194" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review138786751">
  <td colspan="2">
