<div id="review_1383887375" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1383887375" />
    <a title="Loring Wirbel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5593045-loring-wirbel"><img alt="Loring Wirbel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1328030704p2/5593045.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1383887375?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Loring Wirbel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Loring Wirbel" href="/user/show/5593045-loring-wirbel">Loring Wirbel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/26123707-the-ginger-man">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1383887375" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6591744916239194041">Dublin certainly went crazy in the summer of 2015 celebrating the 60th anniversary of Donleavy&apos;s first book. Special forums were held at Trinity College, mere blocks away from Sebastian Dangerfield&apos;s favorite drinking establishments. And Johnny Depp, who has threatened for a decade to produce a film version of <i>The Ginger Man</i> starring himself, was recruited to write a brief but to-the-point foreword to this beautiful Lilliput memorial hardback edition.<br/><br/>So how does Donleavy&apos;s inaugural work hold up</span>
  <span id="freeText6591744916239194041" style="display:none">Dublin certainly went crazy in the summer of 2015 celebrating the 60th anniversary of Donleavy's first book. Special forums were held at Trinity College, mere blocks away from Sebastian Dangerfield's favorite drinking establishments. And Johnny Depp, who has threatened for a decade to produce a film version of <i>The Ginger Man</i> starring himself, was recruited to write a brief but to-the-point foreword to this beautiful Lilliput memorial hardback edition.<br /><br />So how does Donleavy's inaugural work hold up after 60 years? Let's just say I can fully agree with the woman on Goodreads who said she stopped reading because she could not reconcile a book synopsis talking of "satiric and picaresque" with a description of Dangerfield punching his wife in the face because he was in a bad mood. While it's hard to say how much Donleavy resembled his main character, it's clear this book drips misogyny. At the same time, I am empathetic with another woman reviewer who said she enjoyed the book despite its misogyny, because of the quality of its style, and because she does not expect all characters in a novel to be above reproach.<br /><br />There is no doubt Donleavy's film-style streaming prose, filled with close-ups and quick cutaways, is a fascinating bridge between the Joyce of the early 20th century and the later Heller, Vonnegut, and Pynchon. There is also a redemption of sorts in the last 100 pages of the novel when Donleavy at least tries to give his female characters some depth, while showing Dangerfield up to be a deeply troubled individual.<br /><br />There are some who would say that Donleavy is no worse than Hunter Thompson (who admittedly tried to copy Donleavy's style), and that Dangerfield is no worse a character than Yossarian in <i>Catch-22</i> or Benny Profane in <i>V</i>. I disagree. Thompson always carried the pretense of a journalist's mission, while Yossarian and Profane were sympathetic characters full of mixed motives and unusual goals. Sebastian Dangerfield seemed to live to drink to excess, threaten women, and start pointless brawls in pubs, violent orgies that really had no purpose behind them.<br /><br />Then I finally realized that my real problem is that the only Beat authors I can appreciate are the gay ones, like Ginsberg, Ferlinghetti, and Burroughs. Sure, Burroughs was misogynist too, but he tried to anchor his nihilism and dissolution in a broader context. Donleavy resembles Kerouac in certain ways, by wanting to flex a certain macho persona as a rebellion against Cold War manhood, but without taking that rebellion any farther than a life spent becoming an Organization Man.<br /><br />The real rebels of the late 1940s and early 1950s were neither the closet Marxists defending Stalin, nor the macho Beats spinning takes of sound and fury, signifying nothing. The real rebels were the free-jazz musicians and visual artists who promoted alternative culture as though the restrictive, conformist Cold War culture never existed. Many conformist men of the 1950s secretly dreamed of playing Marlon Brando in <i>The Wild One </i>. But being a leader of a motorcycle gang that beat people to death with tire chains was all too much like the Beat Boys, playing their games of excess.<br /><br />Let's raise a glass of Guinness to Donleavy, particularly since he is still alive and nearing 90, and has been praised by many as being a "true gentleman." We can enjoy his prose with a certain amount of detachment, while realizing there's no way to excuse the anti-woman violence, even when 60 years are taken into account. What we should have the courage to do, however, is to admit that the heterosexual side of Beat culture of the 1950s really sucked.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6591744916239194041" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


