    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_613074200" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/613074200" />
    <a title="Brent Mckay" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14223953-brent-mckay"><img alt="Brent Mckay" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1351962904p2/14223953.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/613074200?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brent Mckay" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brent Mckay" href="/user/show/14223953-brent-mckay">Brent Mckay</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer613074200" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18404479349333149198">it must be some sort of literary masterstroke to make me read and mostly enjoy 350 pages about an unlikable sociopath. this book made me want to shower very thoroughly afterwards...and then have some tea. writing this, i feel like i have a filth caked on me from having witnessed Donleavy&apos;s transgressions and yet stayed with him/the book afterwards, somehow empathizing enough to where Donleavy made me part of Dangerfield&apos;s mistakes, and yet capable of the very empathy of which Dangerfield is not.</span>
  <span id="freeText18404479349333149198" style="display:none">it must be some sort of literary masterstroke to make me read and mostly enjoy 350 pages about an unlikable sociopath. this book made me want to shower very thoroughly afterwards...and then have some tea. writing this, i feel like i have a filth caked on me from having witnessed Donleavy's transgressions and yet stayed with him/the book afterwards, somehow empathizing enough to where Donleavy made me part of Dangerfield's mistakes, and yet capable of the very empathy of which Dangerfield is not.<br /><br />Donleavy's language, at its best, is irresistible and musical--i found myself obliged to read the more amazing passages out loud. the book offers great insights on ambition and depression and denial and hunger of all sorts: for companionship, for control, to be wealthy, stuffed with rich food &amp; tea, protected from the raw climate.<br /><br />Donleavy's 3rd and 1st person switches are constant, seamless, and very interesting. <br /><br />The first half is far better than the second, but still a book that stays with you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18404479349333149198" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

